00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:43.200
Clone with a tie: The main argument in favor
of interest groups has to do with pluralism.

00:04:43.210 --> 00:04:46.660
If all interest groups are free to compete
to influence officials, then they'll balance

00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:50.590
each other out. It'll be cool. The idea of
incorporating lots of groups goes back at

00:04:50.590 --> 00:04:55.220
least as far as James Madison. In the Federalist
Papers, Madison argued for extending the sphere

00:04:55.220 --> 00:04:58.650
in American politics and encouraging more
and more factions. The theory was that the

00:04:58.650 --> 00:05:02.460
more groups there were, the less likely that
any one group could gain a corrupting influence

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:06.440
over the government. Sort of like the idea
of the wisdom of crowds or Condorcet's jury

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:09.960
theorem. With more interest groups providing
more information, we will get policies that

00:05:09.960 --> 00:05:12.090
are the result of thoughtful compromise.

00:05:12.090 --> 00:05:15.830
Another argument for interest groups is that
they offer more opportunity for participation

00:05:15.830 --> 00:05:19.930
in politics. Elections only happen every two
years, on the federal level at least, but

00:05:19.930 --> 00:05:24.150
policy gets made all the time, or at least,
it's supposed to. By joining an interest group,

00:05:24.150 --> 00:05:28.530
an individual can push for a policy that care
about all the time, not just at election time.

00:05:28.530 --> 00:05:32.740
And isn't participation the essence of democracy?
I think yes.

00:05:32.740 --> 00:05:36.440
Clone without a tie: Sure, it's great to have
more voices involved in policy making as long

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:40.680
as each voice is powerful enough to be heard.
In the current system, that is just not the case.

00:05:40.680 --> 00:05:44.100
Interest group politics diminishes American
democracy because some interest groups are

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:47.960
so powerful that their voices are able to
crowd out all the others. And in America today,

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:51.040
the people with the loudest voices are the
wealthy! (loudly) And me right now!

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:54.120
And it's not only because the wealthy have
more money to give to politicians; although

00:05:54.120 --> 00:05:58.250
that does help. Obviously, people who are
really poor can't offer campaign contributions,

00:05:58.250 --> 00:06:02.000
but there are plenty of advocates for them.
But in America, the wealthy have other resources

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:06.550
that the poor just can't bring to bear. Like
money! Lotsa, lotsa, money! They tend to be

00:06:06.550 --> 00:06:10.430
better educated, so they have access to more
information, and the ability to disseminate

00:06:10.430 --> 00:06:14.419
their views more (stumbling over the word)
articulately. And just as important, wealthy

00:06:14.419 --> 00:06:17.169
people have more time to devote to political
participation than the poor.

00:06:17.169 --> 00:06:19.509
Clone with a tie: Sure, what you're saying
makes sense, but do you have any proof? I

00:06:19.509 --> 00:06:23.520
